\nThe human solution is about 29 actions. If the character moves RIGHT ~9 times and DOWN ~8 times to reach the green frame, that's 17 actions. Then maybe rotate and enter, which is a few more actions. That's about 20-25 actions total.\nBut I've been moving the character around inefficiently. Let me try to reset and take a more direct approach.\nActually, I can't reset. Let me try to figure out the current state and what needs to happen.\nLooking at the current image, the character is horizontal with red blocks to the left. The green frame is below. Maybe I need to:\n1. Move the character to align with the green frame\n2. Rotate to the correct orientation\n3. Enter the green frame\nLet me try moving DOWN and RIGHT to get the character back to the green frame, then try to enter it.\nActually, let me first check if there's a pattern I'm missing. The green frame has an opening on the left side. The character needs to enter from the left. When the character is upright (facing up), the red feet are at the bottom. When the character is horizontal (facing right), the red feet are on the left.\nSo maybe the correct orientation is horizontal (facing right), with the red feet on the left, and the character needs to enter the green frame from the left side.\nLet me try moving the character to align with the green frame's opening and then move RIGHT to enter.", "kind": "reasoning", "inContext": false}, {"label": "TOOL CALL: python", "content": "<tool_call>\n<function=python>\n<parameter=code>\n# Character is horizontal, facing right. Green frame is below-right.\n# Need to move DOWN to align with green frame, then RIGHT to enter.\n# Let me check positions first\nseg = current_frame.segmentation\nnodes = seg['nodes']\nfor n in nodes:\n    if n['color'] in ['W', 'N', 'R']:\n        print(f\"  id={n['id']}, color={n['color']}, pixels={n['pixels']}, boundary={n['boundary']}\")\n\n# Try moving DOWN to align with green frame, then RIGHT to enter\naction(['DOWN', 'DOWN', 'RIGHT', 'RIGHT